1193 // Helper: Lightweight std::vector<> like class to avoid dragging dependencies (also: Windows implementation of STL with debug enabled is absurdly slow, so let's bypass it so our code runs fast in debug).
1194 // *Important* Our implementation does NOT call C++ constructors/destructors. This is intentional, we do not require it but you have to be mindful of that. Do not use this class as a straight std::vector replacement in your code!
1195 template<typename T>
1196 class ImVector
1197 {
1198 public:
1199  int Size;
1200  int Capacity;
1201  T* Data;
1202 
1203  typedef T value_type;
1204  typedef value_type* iterator;
1205  typedef const value_type* const_iterator;
1206 
1207  inline ImVector() { Size = Capacity = 0; Data = NULL; }
1208  inline ~ImVector() { if (Data) ImGui::MemFree(Data); }
1209  inline ImVector(const ImVector<T>& src) { Size = Capacity = 0; Data = NULL; operator=(src); }
1210  inline ImVector& operator=(const ImVector<T>& src) { clear(); resize(src.Size); memcpy(Data, src.Data, (size_t)Size * sizeof(value_type)); return *this; }
1211 
1212  inline bool empty() const { return Size == 0; }
1213  inline int size() const { return Size; }
1214  inline int capacity() const { return Capacity; }
1215  inline value_type& operator[](int i) { IM_ASSERT(i < Size); return Data[i]; }
1216  inline const value_type& operator[](int i) const { IM_ASSERT(i < Size); return Data[i]; }
1217 
1218  inline void clear() { if (Data) { Size = Capacity = 0; ImGui::MemFree(Data); Data = NULL; } }
1219  inline iterator begin() { return Data; }
1220  inline const_iterator begin() const { return Data; }
1221  inline iterator end() { return Data + Size; }
1222  inline const_iterator end() const { return Data + Size; }
1223  inline value_type& front() { IM_ASSERT(Size > 0); return Data[0]; }
1224  inline const value_type& front() const { IM_ASSERT(Size > 0); return Data[0]; }
1225  inline value_type& back() { IM_ASSERT(Size > 0); return Data[Size - 1]; }
1226  inline const value_type& back() const { IM_ASSERT(Size > 0); return Data[Size - 1]; }
1227  inline void swap(ImVector<value_type>& rhs) { int rhs_size = rhs.Size; rhs.Size = Size; Size = rhs_size; int rhs_cap = rhs.Capacity; rhs.Capacity = Capacity; Capacity = rhs_cap; value_type* rhs_data = rhs.Data; rhs.Data = Data; Data = rhs_data; }
1228 
1229  inline int _grow_capacity(int sz) const { int new_capacity = Capacity ? (Capacity + Capacity/2) : 8; return new_capacity > sz ? new_capacity : sz; }
1230  inline void resize(int new_size) { if (new_size > Capacity) reserve(_grow_capacity(new_size)); Size = new_size; }
1231  inline void resize(int new_size,const value_type& v){ if (new_size > Capacity) reserve(_grow_capacity(new_size)); if (new_size > Size) for (int n = Size; n < new_size; n++) memcpy(&Data[n], &v, sizeof(v)); Size = new_size; }
1232  inline void reserve(int new_capacity)
1233  {
1234  if (new_capacity <= Capacity)
1235  return;
1236  value_type* new_data = (value_type*)ImGui::MemAlloc((size_t)new_capacity * sizeof(value_type));
1237  if (Data)
1238  memcpy(new_data, Data, (size_t)Size * sizeof(value_type));
1239  ImGui::MemFree(Data);
1240  Data = new_data;
1241  Capacity = new_capacity;
1242  }
1243 
1244  // NB: &v cannot be pointing inside the ImVector Data itself! e.g. v.push_back(v[10]) is forbidden.
1245  inline void push_back(const value_type& v) { if (Size == Capacity) reserve(_grow_capacity(Size + 1)); memcpy(&Data[Size], &v, sizeof(v)); Size++; }
1246  inline void pop_back() { IM_ASSERT(Size > 0); Size--; }
1247  inline void push_front(const value_type& v) { if (Size == 0) push_back(v); else insert(Data, v); }
1248  inline iterator erase(const_iterator it) { IM_ASSERT(it >= Data && it < Data+Size); const ptrdiff_t off = it - Data; memmove(Data + off, Data + off + 1, ((size_t)Size - (size_t)off - 1) * sizeof(value_type)); Size--; return Data + off; }
1249  inline iterator insert(const_iterator it, const value_type& v) { IM_ASSERT(it >= Data && it <= Data+Size); const ptrdiff_t off = it - Data; if (Size == Capacity) reserve(_grow_capacity(Size + 1)); if (off < (int)Size) memmove(Data + off + 1, Data + off, ((size_t)Size - (size_t)off) * sizeof(value_type)); memcpy(&Data[off], &v, sizeof(v)); Size++; return Data + off; }
1250  inline bool contains(const value_type& v) const { const T* data = Data; const T* data_end = Data + Size; while (data < data_end) if (*data++ == v) return true; return false; }
1251 };

1326 // Helper: Simple Key->value storage
1327 // Typically you don't have to worry about this since a storage is held within each Window.
1328 // We use it to e.g. store collapse state for a tree (Int 0/1)
1329 // This is optimized for efficient lookup (dichotomy into a contiguous buffer) and rare insertion (typically tied to user interactions aka max once a frame)
1330 // You can use it as custom user storage for temporary values. Declare your own storage if, for example:
1331 // - You want to manipulate the open/close state of a particular sub-tree in your interface (tree node uses Int 0/1 to store their state).
1332 // - You want to store custom debug data easily without adding or editing structures in your code (probably not efficient, but convenient)
1333 // Types are NOT stored, so it is up to you to make sure your Key don't collide with different types.
1334 struct ImGuiStorage
1335 {
1336  struct Pair
1337  {
1338  ImGuiID key;
1339  union { int val_i; float val_f; void* val_p; };
1340  Pair(ImGuiID _key, int _val_i) { key = _key; val_i = _val_i; }
1341  Pair(ImGuiID _key, float _val_f) { key = _key; val_f = _val_f; }
1342  Pair(ImGuiID _key, void* _val_p) { key = _key; val_p = _val_p; }
1343  };
1344  ImVector<Pair> Data;
1345 
1346  // - Get***() functions find pair, never add/allocate. Pairs are sorted so a query is O(log N)
1347  // - Set***() functions find pair, insertion on demand if missing.
1348  // - Sorted insertion is costly, paid once. A typical frame shouldn't need to insert any new pair.
1349  void Clear() { Data.clear(); }

1358 
1359  // - Get***Ref() functions finds pair, insert on demand if missing, return pointer. Useful if you intend to do Get+Set.

1475 // Helper: Manually clip large list of items.
1476 // If you are submitting lots of evenly spaced items and you have a random access to the list, you can perform coarse clipping based on visibility to save yourself from processing those items at all.
1477 // The clipper calculates the range of visible items and advance the cursor to compensate for the non-visible items we have skipped.
1478 // ImGui already clip items based on their bounds but it needs to measure text size to do so. Coarse clipping before submission makes this cost and your own data fetching/submission cost null.
1479 // Usage:
1480 // ImGuiListClipper clipper(1000); // we have 1000 elements, evenly spaced.
1481 // while (clipper.Step())
1482 // for (int i = clipper.DisplayStart; i < clipper.DisplayEnd; i++)
1483 // ImGui::Text("line number %d", i);
1484 // - Step 0: the clipper let you process the first element, regardless of it being visible or not, so we can measure the element height (step skipped if we passed a known height as second arg to constructor).
1485 // - Step 1: the clipper infer height from first element, calculate the actual range of elements to display, and position the cursor before the first element.
1486 // - (Step 2: dummy step only required if an explicit items_height was passed to constructor or Begin() and user call Step(). Does nothing and switch to Step 3.)
1487 // - Step 3: the clipper validate that we have reached the expected Y position (corresponding to element DisplayEnd), advance the cursor to the end of the list and then returns 'false' to end the loop.
1488 struct ImGuiListClipper
1489 {
1490  float StartPosY;
1491  float ItemsHeight;
1492  int ItemsCount, StepNo, DisplayStart, DisplayEnd;
1493 
1494  // items_count: Use -1 to ignore (you can call Begin later). Use INT_MAX if you don't know how many items you have (in which case the cursor won't be advanced in the final step).
1495  // items_height: Use -1.0f to be calculated automatically on first step. Otherwise pass in the distance between your items, typically GetTextLineHeightWithSpacing() or GetFrameHeightWithSpacing().
1496  // If you don't specify an items_height, you NEED to call Step(). If you specify items_height you may call the old Begin()/End() api directly, but prefer calling Step().
1497  ImGuiListClipper(int items_count = -1, float items_height = -1.0f) { Begin(items_count, items_height); } // NB: Begin() initialize every fields (as we allow user to call Begin/End multiple times on a same instance if they want).
1498  ~ImGuiListClipper() { IM_ASSERT(ItemsCount == -1); } // Assert if user forgot to call End() or Step() until false.

1512 // Draw callback may be useful for example, A) Change your GPU render state, B) render a complex 3D scene inside a UI element (without an intermediate texture/render target), etc.
